 and plays influenced the work of many well-known writers and artists: Jean Cocteau found in him "genius in its pure state," while Salvador Dalí, who died with a copy of Roussel's Impressions d'Afrique on his bedside table, believed him to be one of France's greatest writers ever. Edmond Rostand, Marcel Duchamp, André Breton, Michel Foucault, and Alain Robbe-Grillet all testified to the power of his unique imagination.By any standards, Roussel led an extraordinary life. Tremendously wealthy, he took two world tours during which he hardly left his hotel rooms. He never wore his clothes more than twice, and generally avoided conversation because he dreaded that it might turn morbid. Ford, himself a poet, traces the evolution of Roussel's bizarre compositional methods and describes the idiosyncrasies of a life structured as obsessively as Roussel structured his writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 4aEurope. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aAshbery, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshbery, John.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172414540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501724145.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles